      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brine the chicken",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Combine the {{buttermilk}}, brine {{sea-salt-fine}} of salt, brine {{garlic-powder}} of garlic powder, and brine {{cayenne}} of cayenne in a large bowl. Add the {{chicken-drumsticks}} and {{chicken-thigh}}.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Cover and refrigerate for at least 8 hours or overnight.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make the coating and coat the chicken",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Set up a wide shallow bowl. Tip in the {{plain-flour}}, {{cornflour}}, {{paprika-smoked}}, coating {{garlic-powder}}, {{onion-powder}}, coating {{cayenne}}, coating {{black-pepper}}, and coating {{sea-salt-fine}}. Whisk to mix.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Remove a piece of chicken from the buttermilk and allow the excess to drip for a few seconds. Press the chicken firmly into the flour mixture, turning and pressing to build up a thick coating. Place on a wire rack. Repeat with all pieces. Leave to rest for 10 minutes.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Fry the chicken",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Heat the {{vegetable-oil}} in a large deep saucepan to 170°C. Keep the pan on at least a medium-high heat throughout so the oil recovers temperature between batches.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Fry in batches of 3 or 4 pieces for 12 to 15 minutes for thighs and drumsticks, turning once halfway through, until the crust is deep golden and the internal temperature reads 75°C.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "text": "Drain on kitchen paper and rest for 5 minutes before serving.",
                    "type": "text"
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Keep the oil at 170°C; use a thermometer; fry in batches of 3 to 4 pieces maximum and allow the oil to return to temperature between batches",
              "cause": "Oil temperature too low, or too many pieces added at once",
              "symptom": "Coating has a pale, greasy crust"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Reduce the heat; bone-in chicken takes 12 to 15 minutes and the oil must not be so hot that the crust is done in 5",
              "cause": "Oil too hot",
              "symptom": "Coating is dark outside but the chicken is still raw inside"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Press the coating firmly onto the surface; the buttermilk paste between the meat and the flour is the glue, allow 10 minutes of resting on the rack before frying",
              "cause": "Coating not pressed firmly enough, or chicken wet when coated",
              "symptom": "Coating has not adhered and is falling off in the oil"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Fried chicken is one of the defining dishes of the American South. Its roots are in two cooking traditions that met in the colonial period: Scottish frying in fat, and West African bold seasoning. What emerged is one of the most copied dishes in global cooking. The chain-restaurant version is a distant simplification of the home-cooked original. The home recipe varies by state, by county, and by family.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
